related_questions.snippet: Passion fruit is a beneficial fruit with a healthful nutrition profile. It contains high levels of vitamin A, which is important for skin, vision, and the immune system, and vitamin C, an important antioxidant.

related_questions.question: How do you eat passionfruit?
related_questions.snippet: Enjoy It Fresh Grab a knife (either a chef's knife or a paring knife) and place the passion fruit on a cutting board. Use the knife to cut straight through the passion fruit crosswise (along its equator). Use a spoon to scoop out the flesh and seeds—and enjoy.

list.title: Origin
list.snippet: Passion fruit is native to South America, but is now grown in tropical and subtropical areas around the world, including Australia, New Zealand, and Hawaii.

list.title: Appearance
list.snippet: Passion fruit is round to oval, and can be yellow or purple when ripe. The fruit has a hard rind and a soft, juicy pulp with many seeds.

list.title: Taste
list.snippet: Passion fruit has a sweet and tart flavor with notes of mandarin, orange, and pineapple.

list.title: Health benefits
list.snippet: Passion fruit is a good source of antioxidants, vitamin C, and fiber. It also contains piceatannol, a compound found in the seeds that may help improve insulin sensitivity and reduce the risk of type 2 diabetes.

list.title: Preparation
list.snippet: To eat passion fruit, you can slice it in half and scoop out the pulp and seeds with a spoon. You can also use the pulp in juices, ice cream, desserts, and other drinks.

list.title: How to select
list.snippet: When choosing a passion fruit, look for one that feels heavy, has wrinkled skin, and gives slightly when squeezed.
